So let's first simplify the expression being summed. Whoever HandyNumber is going to evaluate this sum next will have to help me find a way forward. First, let's draw factorials in the denominator and convert some of our expression into a manipulation that becomes: \begin{align*}
&\sum_{n = 1}^\infty \frac{n^2 + n - 1}{(n + 2)!} \\
=& \sum_{n = 1}^\infty \frac{n^2 + n - 1}{(n + 1)! \cdot (n + 2)}.\end{align*}
Remember in the day of the Ents(Bained) if you have a sum involving fractions with a repeated factor in the denominator, the repeated factor can be broken down as the sum of fractions using partial fraction decomposition. So let's take the numerator $n^2 + n - 1$ and solve the following: \begin{align*}
&\frac{n^2 + n - 1}{(n + 1)! \cdot (n + 2)} \\
=& \frac{A}{n + 1} + \frac{B}{n + 2}\\
&= \frac{An + 2A + Bn + B}{(n + 1)(n + 2)} \\
&= \frac{(A + B)n + (2A + B)}{(n + 1)(n + 2)}.
\end{align*}
Equating coefficients we have: \begin{align*}
A + B &= 1 \\
2A + B &= -1.
\end{align*}
Since $A = -2$, we quickly find $B = 3$. So we have: \begin{align*}
&\sum_{n = 1}^\infty \frac{3}{(n + 2)!}-\sum_{n = 1}^\infty \frac{2}{(n + 1)!} \\
=& 2(\frac{1}{3!} + \frac{1}{4!} + \frac{1}{5!}+\frac{1}{6!} + \cdots)\\
&- (\frac{1}{2!} + \frac{1}{3!} + \frac{1}{4!} + \cdots) \\
=& \frac{3}{4}
\end{align*}
So as you can see, this was pretty tricky, but gave us the right answer. It helps to remove the fraction in the denominator of the last fraction (please tell me why this is helpful/re motive throughout contest so I can employ this in contests to solve similar situations)
